text:
will this be the â€œmidterm of the women?â€ many have hailed 2018 as the â€œyear of the womenâ€ as weâ€™ve seen a surge of women voice their dissent, from the demonstrations surrounding brett kavanaughâ€™s supreme court confirmation to the more than 20,000 women and men who walked out of google last week to protest the tech giantâ€™s mishandling of sexual harassment allegations.

this tuesday the collective sense of â€œenough is enoughâ€ that has fueled the #metoo and #timesup movements will be tested on the political stage. there is a record number of female candidates running for office in the midterm elections, hoping to turn anger into action. frustrated that their voices arenâ€™t being heard and anxious as they see government policies focused on womenâ€™s rights, healthcare and family wellbeing stall or rollback; women are stepping up.

these female congressional nominees are adding to the most diverse pool of candidates in u.s. history. according to the new york times, â€œmore than a quarter of all the candidates running this year are female, including 84 women of color â€” a 42 percent increase from just two years ago.â€ the themes that run across all these womenâ€™s campaigns include women and minority representation, equal pay, healthcare, education and jobs. there are women on both sides of gun control, tax reform, national security and immigration issues but almost all shared a desire to help their communities work together.

regardless of how tuesday turns out, these women have created a collective call-to-action and are serving as inspiration for more women to run for office. itâ€™s known that women candidates face an uphill battle, receiving less funding than men and being held to different standards. but these women are not letting these facts deter them because they believe we need more women candidates and more women elected, not just on tuesday but also in the next elections. hereâ€™s hoping that every win and loss in the midterms inspires more women to run in 2020.  #sexyaftersexualassault  #votewomen #woundedwarrior #mentoo #equality #empower #supportoneanother #empowerwomen #alllivesmatter #feministpositivity #lovenothateâ¤ï¸ #getoutandvote2018 #getoutandvote #feminism

text:
funny how the universe gives you quirky reminders to smile even in the most stressful times... .
.
iâ€™m that guy who figures out how to carry 20 grocery bags from the car in one trip with starbucks in hand. today was no exception at the office as i picked up my mail, prepared my breakfastâ€”eggs with a fruit parfaitâ€”starbucks in hand and headed back to my desk which is on the opposite end of the suite. meanwhile, my anxiety level on election day today echoes that of my liberal peers who are demanding change through our right to #vote. balancing it all, trying not to drop anything, i finally made it to my desk and no joke set this package down on my desk as is and chuckled.
.
.
todayâ€™s going to matter in so many ways. whether we see the blue wave thatâ€™s been predicted, or suffer utter disappointment like we did two years ago, i know one thingâ€”that among it all iâ€™ve been able to still smile. i smile with my friends and family whoâ€™ve accepted my homosexuality since day one. i smile in encouragement of the brave women whoâ€™ve told their stories and are finally being heard. i smile in awe as people of color refuse to let the odds define them and rise up to enact change and demand justice in a culture dominated by white privilege. i smile at the jewish community in pittsburgh who came together amongst tragedy and told trump he is not welcome and that his condolences are worthless without definitively condemning the acts of neo-nazi domestic terrorists.. .
.
we are all responsible for making this world a better place. we are responsible for seeing the humanity in every single human being. .
.
and for those who persist on stripping that humanity away through racism, misogyny, xenophobia, terror, and pure evil... know this... you will not win, we will rise up and stand together with smiles on our faces, even when you knock us down, because we are more resilient and fearless than ever. 
#justvoted #nottodaysatan #smile #bluewave #riseabove #gohigh #blacklivesmatter #metoo

text:
â€œone day i had a revelation about forgiveness. i learnt that forgiveness is a choice and not a feeling, so i came to my battleground and chose to forgive the man who abused me...â€
â€¢
i had been believing a lie about forgiveness. i believed that i had to feel ready to forgive and that this feeling of forgiveness would come before making the choice. 
but i learnt that forgiveness isnâ€™t a feeling, itâ€™s a choice; an act of will and a way to take power away from the pain
â€¢ 
here are some other common forgiveness myths:
1) â€œforgiveness is saying that what happened was okay.â€ no. forgiveness and justice are not the same. 
forgiveness is about giving yourself permission to heal. it is not giving permission for harm.
2) â€œforgiveness will mean we need to be friends again.â€ no. where danger or toxicity in the relationship remains, you do not need to be reconciled to the person who hurt you. you can still put physical, emotional and relational boundaries in place and forgiveness can help facilitate these boundaries. 
3) â€œdonâ€™t they need to say sorry, first?â€ no. if this was true, some of us would be waiting a lifetime! as joyce meyer says, â€™unforgiveness is like drinking poison and expecting the other person to dieâ€™. forgiveness is a gift to yourself and you can give it any time you choose to and itâ€™s a gift worth fighting for
â€¢
so, go ahead today, find your battleground
â€¢
why not get in touch with @mercyukorg support services if you want any more information, resources, prayer or support for your forgiveness journey or check out week 4 in mercyâ€™s keys to freedom discipleship workbook available on the website

vote for health care access 
vote to protect black womxn

vote for financial stability 
vote for native american rights 
vote for mental and physical disabilities
vote for education (and itâ€™s reform) 
vote against mass incarceration 
vote against domestic violence 
vote for lgbtq rights
vote to end white supremacy.
.ğŸ¦‹.
also ask yourself: what can i do to make voting more accessible to others ? how can i volunteer?

text:
today is election day. i hope as you are voting, you think of finian and our family. i hope you vote to protect us and our healthcare. i hope you vote to not erase us,  to not take away our rights. i hope you remember finian when you vote to protect the environment, i hope you want to give them a planet to live on, animals to love, air to breathe. i hope you vote so they'll never have to say me too, never have to hide from a school shooter, never have to see their friends killed by cops or nazis. i hope that if you ever think these issues are just about economic freedom, you remember a smiling baby in sheep pajamas who needs you to vote to protect their life. please don't erase finian. please don't take away their healthcare. please vote democrat. .
.

text:
sharing books to children to support their education 
kudos to teachers that sacrifice their comfort to ensure children in community of aiyetoro budo and environment access quality education 
a community without no commercial means of transportation and it's over 25 kilometer to the transport park

supporting aiyetoro budo and neighbouring communities with education supplies and mini library with various textbooks and work books which was presented to the school management during our rural outreach in collaboration with funaab-amrec, gendi and stecom books

education is essential to a child's development and its a key to break poverty gap in the rural areas because every child deserves the best start in life, which is what we and our partners are working to provide the world's most vulnerable children. education is essential to a child's development

as organisation we encourage people
to join our mission to make education a reality for children throughout the world especially for rural areas.Â 
presentation and distribution of education materials was championed by dr. oalekan olakunle professor grace sokoya and dr o. j olaoye of federal university of agriculture, abeokuta. - amrec and professor ashimolowo olubunmi of gender development initiative (gendi)

text:
v for vendetta (5/8) "remember, remember, the 5th of november..."
as the world is going towards a direction that seems to speak only words of hate, that seems to have as its one and only purpose to strip away human rights from as many people as possible, and as we approach here in new york an election day that feels as crucial as it ever has, i feel like sharing this old monologue i recorded from v for vendetta.
because only love can make us fearless. and if we don't learn to love each other, to protect each other, to support and have hope for each other, even for those we don't know, there will be no tomorrow, no hope, and no light to beak through these dark, dark days.
and, once again: for all the times i've been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you don't want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i've been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an artist, as a free person and an activist, this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i won't stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you don't agree with it, fine. but you won't shut my mouth, you won't stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.
#5thofnovember #vforvendetta #agirlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
i had the profound pleasure of attending a lecture last night with my daughter and her friends with tarana burke, founder of the #metoo movement.  the lecture was hosted by ucsb in coordination with their black studies & feminist studies departments. 
it was fascinating to hear how her  work and activism began at such an early age. her mother had her reading marcus garvey and malcolm x at a young age and nurtured this queenâ€™s voice from the start. ğŸ‘‘ 
there were loads of old white ladies (like me) in attendance. i visibly noticed their presence from the beginning as it struck me as odd since this was a sold out event designed by and for college students. after the awe inspiring lecture and personal testimony by tarana there was the to be expected q & a.  i was downright appalled at what happened next. both isles immediately filled up with said â€œold white ladiesâ€ on a mission. they all yes all had a self centered pitch to promote themselves. several times tarana had to cut them short and say â€œplease tell me what your question for â€˜meâ€™ is?â€ this broke my heart for at the end of the isles were african american girls (students)  patiently waiting in line to ask tarana about â€œherâ€ work and activism.  this was white privilege co-opting at itâ€™s finest. yes i was tempted to shut that down, but then that would of been very old white lady of â€œmeâ€ as well as this was a student event. i literally wanted to call some of our san diego queens to quickly educate and advise me in that particular moment. i didnâ€™t do anything except sit there in dismay. now this morning feeling saddened and ashamed. it was a teaching moment for all i realize. i will be meeting  with my daughter and her friends this morning to â€œhearâ€ their reflections. all african american young college girls.

text:
today is the day we have been waiting for! time to get out and vote ğŸ‡ºğŸ‡¸ the last election day i woke up incredibly drunk with no memory of the night before, my boss was calling me because i was scheduled to be presenting in front of a large group in ten minutes. 
as i put it together and realized what was happening i wanted to die. there was a man's shirt in my bed and i still have no idea where it came from or how i got to my hotel room. 
i was written up and received a final written warning and they told me if it happens again i will be terminated. one of the other two incidents involved alcohol and i felt out of control. i had never expected this to happen to me. i have tried hard my entire life to follow the rules and be successful but alcohol was something beyond my control. 
that evening donald trump became president and i felt like the entire world changed in 24 hours. 
three months later i checked myself into @passagesmalibu determined to change

text:
part of #healing and moving through feelings of #guilt and #shame is finding allies, people who #inspire and remind you of your #beauty and divine #nature. healing is the heart of the many global movements for #reparations and #decolonization.

healing is the polar opposite of what most of the world's political and business leadership seek to sell. hence the pithy hashtag #googleprotectssexualpredators, which speaks to my own sorry experiences over the last four years.

if you know me and my work, you know that i write a lot about guilt and shame as currencies. i also talk about using them to fund healing projects such as a #migratinguniversity and #decolonialbusinessacademy. itâ€™s true.

while iâ€™d rather not shame and guilt people and companies into giving monies, we need the cash. i do. just read my article, â€œ$6.42 and the dreamâ€ on linkedin. believe me, i don't want to remember the how and why of how @google has been protecting one sexual predator that i know by name and many others such as #andyrubin, but sometimes we can't forget or move forward without a formal reckoning and financial reparations.

that's what #metoo and #timesup and #niunamenos and #balancetonporc represent: reckoning and reparations.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
last night, @reflectionsofmyselfie and i saw @taranajaneen speak at ucsb. it was incredible to listen to tarana burke talk about her years of organizing for social justice, how her experiences informed her creation of #metoo, and how we move forward from this moment. there were so many things discussed last night (i literally laughed and cried), but there were two themes in particular that i think are paramount. 1) me too is not about taking down perpetrators or revelling in salacious scandals. itâ€™s about creating and maintaining space for survivors of sexual assault to heal. we should be listening to and lifting up survivors, not writing think pieces about whether itâ€™s too soon for louis ck to do stand up again. and 2) we have a lack of moral leadership in the united states right now, which means *we* are the moral leaders. itâ€™s on us to build the communities we need, by organizing and taking ownership of the work we each have to do to ensure a better future. itâ€™s easy to imbue a celebrity figure or politician with all our hopes and dreams, but that allows us to tap out of the responsibility we have to ourselves and the people around us to improve our own lives. tarana burke is not going to end sexual violence or make a definitive statement on gender equality in the us, but she can inspire all of us to take action with her. .
.
one important step you can take *today* is to vote, and tell everyone you know to do it too.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#feminism #feminist #equality #vote #votevotevote #votethemout #midterms #midterms2018

evocative piece by @lindeezimmer. perhaps it's the times which we live in, but i've been especially drawn to mystical or supernatural representations of women lately â€“ mermaids, witches, goddesses.

from the literal witch hunts hundreds of years ago to the continued harassment of those who've spoken out in the #metoo movement. from continued fights for reproductive justice, equal pay, political representation. in a world where the legislative and institutional power of women and our intersections with other marginalized groups continues to languish, there's something oddly comforting about visceral fire and brimstone representations of female strength.

text:
after a miracle fueled experience @soul_camp, i am inspired, renewed and am totally certain that what got me here, wonâ€™t get me there. â£
â£
this means itâ€™s time to dig even deeper than ever,  recommit to my goals, and get laser focused on putting in the time to bring them to life. writing down my goals daily will help me stick to a writing schedule and remind me to go on dates. â£
â£
what can i say?!? i want the book and the boyfriendğŸ¤— â£
â£
the great news is itâ€™s all within reach, i integrated this practice into my life 3 years ago when i went through a divorce. i was intent on walking through the process with grace and dignity so i wrote about how i would do just that every day. guess what, it happened. exactly as i planned. i was blown away.â£
â£
i am certain that whatever i envision is possible but its not pure manifestation. it will take focus, dedication and developing a knowing that the universe is co- creating my dream with me. â£
â£
from my experience, dreamweaving requires a lot of connecting quietly with myself and thinking positive thoughts. but this time, iâ€™m reaching so high that iâ€™ll need to become intimately involved with my divinity and to vision with a higher purpose as my guide. â£
â£
tbh, i have no idea what this means or how it feels or how it will come to life. but i know as long as i can name it, claim it and envision it, especially the emotions that i will feel when having the book and the boyfriend, it is possible. i donâ€™t have to worry about the how, just be open to what the universe serves up. â£
â£
and i am. with arms wide open.

text:
wild woman retreats seek to transform the perception of what it means to be a woman. 
now, more than ever, there is an urgency for women to wake up to who we really are. 
to understand where we came from, who came before us, and all that holds influence over our sovereignty - so we can move forward with knowledge and truth and mindful action. 
wild woman retreats do not seek to change, improve, or fix women. women donâ€™t need to be fixed. itâ€™s our perception of women that needs to change.

women need only to remember all that they innately are. to soften into loving ourselves in all our forms and phases. 
wild woman retreats provide the space, education, experience, and authentic community connection to help women reclaim who they really are. all while resetting and getting away from it all in beautiful locations around the world.

join us this feb for another wild adventure in mexico.

discover your aliveness. discover you. 
wild woman baja
feb 9-14th, 2019

click the link in bio to learn more!

text:
you know those times in your life that it seems there is no way out? 
i felt like that as a little girl not knowing who my mother was. i felt like that every time i was being abused by people that were suppose to protect me. i felt like that at age 13 when i no longer felt like there was a reason to live. i felt like that as i tried to put the pieces of my history back together and when i was searching for my dad. i know what itâ€™s like to feel completely hopeless. i also know the profound love and mercy of god. at times when it seemed there was no other way, he made a way. .
.
.

women in america were the last minority in america to be granted the constitutional right to vote. women have been in america since its founding around 500 years ago, and just 98 years ago, received the right to vote. they saw how they had been the foundation of america for decades and then saw men from europe that would just automatically have the right to vote because he was a man, even though he had just arrived.
to the women of america: you have a duty to use your constitutional right to vote. suffrage activists suffered at the hands of bigotry for nearly a century fighting for just their right to vote. just imagine if you lived in their time. you would have had virtually no rights and lived by what men told you to do. you have a chance to make your voice heard today and not have any man tell you what to do. please go out and vote in this election for the soul of our nation. honor the women who came before you!

text:
i was writing a paper on child abuse and the cases i had to go through broke my heart. i believe it was agatha christie who said that the luckiest thing that can happen is to have a happy childhood. to imagine hands that are supposed to be anchors gropping at innocence, snatching it away, making children they are supposed to love uncomfortable , it turns my stomach. however controversial, diluted the me too movement might be the implications must be paid attention too. it is hard to speak up god damnit. it is hard for us, it is even harder for our children. i think it is more about how well we communicate with them than about their guts or voice. we must find our voices and hope to god that  will help unglue other tongues.

text:
a story of the closed windows and doors where no one speaks and just live with the "let it be, the way it is" attitude. no one has problem until the person who is suffering speaks up,  and then we all gather to raise questions instead of supporting. .. some may ignore, some doesn't even care but most of us will question of them being true. 
why now?.. it has been in practice since so long so why speak now?.. why do you care about him/her? ... you are a liar. .. in between these things we all do open the doors but forget to open the windows.
..
same like everyone of us accept the social causes and speak about them with the clear notion of hope that everything will be alright. but when it comes to our family and elders why we stop?..
.. confronting ourselves that they are elder of our family we should not speak? ..
..
i think the change start from us. ğŸ’“ğŸŒ 
..
..
hope you all get it ğŸŒ ğŸŒ 
..

text:
approaching art /
approaching life
.
.
it's not "why can't i do this?"
.
sometimes, you can't.  it may not be in your control;
perhaps you simply lack the knowledge or perspective right now.
perhaps your difficulty stems from a lack of means.
sometimes, outside forces will stop you.  it happens!
#thestruggleisreal
.
asking "why" will only get you as far as seeing someone else's perspective.  you will depend on outside sources for "the answer".
.
it can be a starting point.  however, there is a danger in asking only "why". it can become a cycle of opinions and self-doubt.
.
if you start asking how, you will open the pathways to progress:
.
how did i get here?
(will lead you to where you are going)
how can i get there?
(will lead you to what you need)
how did they get there?
(will help you see another's humanity)
how did they do that?
(you will learn they had the knowledge and/or means)
.
additionally, if you ask "how" and find you don't have the means, you can free yourself from the worry that it is something you're doing "wrong".
it's not you.
stop beating yourself up.
we don't control life.
.
if anything, now that you know what the missing components may be, you can determine how to obtain them and make that change.
.
.
the realest question is:
"how can i do this?"
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
i had a realization that i feel like was really obvious but not so much for me.yesterday i met my friends 10 year old daughter. i'm never around kids. i'm the baby of a tiny family and most of my friends don't have kids. since, i've been thinking about how simple life was back when i was that age but it also made me think about how miserable life was back then. i was molested and abused almost everyday from 9-15. it finally, really clicked that i was just a child. seeing a 10 year old in person reminded me just how young i was. i feel like we spend most of our childhood pretending to be older than we are and wishing we are already grown ups, that we rarely actually realized that we were just kids. â˜†
if this 10 year old told me she was going through even just a tiny bit of what i had, i would have never expected her to give consent. she's a child. i would have never blamed her for what she had been through. she's just a child. i would have never judged her for it. she's just a child. i would have never told her that she deserved it. she is just a child. i would have never thought that her being molested was her fault. she is a child. i would have never gotten mad at her for being manipulated by him. she is just a child. i would have instantly blamed the person who assaulted her for every single one of these things.
â˜†
i've always been so hard on myself, even when i say i'm not hard on myself. i've always blamed myself and gotten mad at myself for what i've been through. i've resented myself for various reason. i've spent a lifetime disassociating. i've always viewed myself as in the wrong and thought of the millions of ways i could have possibly, maybe stopped it. i've always been mean to myself over something that was never my fault. it was his fault. he molested me. he assaulted me. he abused me. he manipulated me. he ruined me. he took away my childhood. he took away my innocence. he took away any kind of confidence i had. he took away my feeling safe in my own home, in my own room, in my own bed. he took away any sort of normalcy or stability that i felt. it is 1000% his fault. i was just a child. â˜†
â˜†healing is one hell of a journey

text:
a natural moisturizer
 jojoba oil has texture and uses similar to that of your natural skin oil. it keeps your oil levels balanced and serves as a strong natural treatment for eczema as well as a home remedy for acne.
jojoba oil is an emollient. it moisturizes our skin, prevents irritations, treats scaly and rough patches. it also forms an oily layer on the top of the skin that traps water in the skin preventing it to go dry. jojoba oil contains no chemicals that lead to any allergic reactions. thus, it can be used for almost every part of your body. learn more link in bio.

 jojoba oil has texture and uses similar to that of your natural skin oil. it keeps your oil levels balanced and serves as a strong natural treatment for eczema as well as a home remedy for acne.

text:
@regran_ed from @magapartyx -  dnc chair tom perez caught off guard when tapper confronts him for sheltering ellison from abuse claim
november 5, 2018 | tom tillison

democratic national committee chairÂ tom perez struggled to defend the decision not to call for the resignation of deputy chairÂ keith ellison, whoâ€™s up against serious allegations of domestic abuse.
perez wasÂ asked by cnn anchor jake tapper, who cited the #metoo movement, why ellison is still vice chair of the party. â€œwhat i say is that we should always take those complaints seriously and we do,â€ he replied. â€œand thatâ€™s why an investigation was conducted, thatâ€™s whyÂ congressman ellisonÂ asked for a house ethics investigation and democrats have never hesitated to take action, unlike republicans.â€
the minnesota democratic party conducted its own investigation and declared that they â€œwere unable to substantiate the claim.â€ in what proved to be a pleasant surprise, tapper did not let perez off the hook so easily.
â€œwait a second, democrats have never hesitated to take action? do you mean in the last year, or do you mean historically?â€ the cnn anchor asked. â€œbecause historically, i could go through a list of people.â€
perez cited al frankin, the democratic senator from minnesota who resigned from the u.s. senate in december 2017 after being accused of groping women and other sexually inappropriate behavior.
â€œdemocrats didnâ€™t hesitate to do something even it was difficult, because it was the right thing to do,â€ he claimed.

equally surprising, tapper brought upÂ ted kennedy and president bill clinton.
â€œjake, iâ€™ve been chair of the democratic national committee for 18 months,â€ he said in response.
ellison is running for attorney general in minnesota.
tapper asked perez if he thought ellisonâ€™s accuser was â€œlying,â€ and the dnc chair danced around the question.
â€œi thinkÂ keith ellisonâ€™s ex-girlfriend deserves to be heard and deserves to be treated with dignity and deserves to have a fair and full investigation,â€ perez said. â€œand that is exactly what has been done.â€
this from the party that claims to be looking out for women.

text:
it's early in the morning
the moon is hardly showing
there are creatures all around
see their shadows hear their sounds
but they're taking me places
places i don't know
it's getting kind of spooky
should i stay or follow?
but they take me by the hand
and whisper in my ear
"there's no need to worry
first lets make that clear
but were gonna take you places
places you will know
they look kind of different
but not to your heart or to your soul
but just open up your senses
and let the light in
you've now reached these gates
so you may as well step in"
.
the mystery unfolds
as she walks along the path
the trees talk to her
finally at last
.
it's a long way home. 
i'll be back at dawn, got to walk this road alone
.
.
.

text:
i can not tell you how long it has taken me to believe and pursue this mentality. my whole life, this year especially, i have doubted who i am and the woman that i am supposed to become.  going into this year i truly believed it was going to be the best year of my life. i turned 21, 18 is my lucky number - stupid i know, and i thought that i had met the guy i was going to marry. when in reality it has been the worste year of my life. i lost some of my closest friends, i survived an abusive relationship, and for the love of god i gained 10lbs. i hit a wall by the time summer rolled around. i told myself i needed a reminder that this life is not just the things we suffer, but the things we overcome, and the lives we build despite what has happened to us. so, i got a tattoo. i permanently wrote the words "i lived" on my ribcage, my reminder that everyday is a new opportunity to do something adventurous and brave. that no matter what i go through, i will live the fairy tale life that i promised myself. i am not saying yall should get a tattoo - it hurts! i am telling you that everyone needs a reminder of how beautiful this life is. i think we lose sight of that when life gets hard. today, my life is 100% different than it was a year ago. i am not saying it's perfect, example - my hot as hell boyfriend is currently snoring next to me - which i have combated with some killer ear buds! i am saying that this year has been a living nightmare, and despite of that nightmare, i am closer to my family, i have amazing friends who make my life incredibly fun, i have an adorable kitty - i'm sure you've all seen her, i post relentlessly, i'm dating the most amazing person i have ever metâ¤â¤, i lost the 10 lbs, and i couldn't be happier. so, despite all the awful, there is a damn ton of amazing! so inhale your fears and exhale your amazing! and for those of you that made it this far.... p.s. i love you!
.
.
.
.
.
.
#metoo #ilived #beautifullife

text:
this is the day...
.
election day 2018!
.
we as women are making history!
.

stacey abrams (d) (@staceyabrams ) of georgia ia running to become the first african-american female governor. .
sharice davids (d) (@shariceforcongress ) of kansas and member of the ho-chunk nation, yvette herrell (r) (@yvetteherrell) of new mexico and member of the cherokee nation and debÂ haaland (d) (@deb4congressnm) of new mexico and member of the pueblo of laguna tribe are all running to be among the first native american congresswomen.
.
either rep. martha mcsally (r) (@repmcsally) or rep. kyrsten sinema (@repsinema) (d) will become arizona's first woman elected to the u.s. senate.
.
christine hallquistÂ (d) (@christineforvermont) of vermont could become the first elected transgender governor. .
rashida tlaibÂ (d) (@rashidatlaib) of michigan and ilhan omar (d) (@ilhanomar) of minnesota could become the first muslim women to be in congress. .
young kim (r) (@youngkimforcongress) of california could become the first korean-american congresswoman. .
as an african-american woman who is of cherokee desecent my spirit is dancing but as a woman i am proud beyond words!
.
let us stand with these women today no matter what race or political party. we are all in this together. if they do we can too! whether they win the election or not they have already won and because of them so have we! .
.
#election2018 #girlgang  #shouldertoshoulder #womensempowerment
#yesyoucan #metoo #historyisbeingmade

while australia celebrates the melbourne cup today, yesterday a former british model, with indelible links to the cup, reached her 76th birthday. ğŸ‡ğŸ¿#melbournecup 
known variously as â€œthe shrimpâ€ and mrs jean cox, she became famous as jean shrimpton, one of the worldâ€™s first supermodels.

on derby day, she made an impact wearing a simple white dress. to modern observers it might look like any other tasteful white dress, but the hemline was 10 centimetres above her knees at a time when most women still wore dresses that covered the knees. the model was also not wearing gloves, stockings or a hat. following her appearance, the front page of the sun newspaper raged: â€œthere she was, the worldâ€™s highest-paid fashion model, snubbing the iron-clad conventions of fashionable flemington with a dress five inches above the knee â€“ no hat, no gloves and no stockings!â€ derby day racegoers were horrified. the press clamoured for photos and, within days, the story of the model in the mini had ignited global controversy. her race-day outfit paved the way for aussie women to embrace bolder, less conservative fashion and the progressive cultural attitudes the decade embodied. the miniskirt was born. seems so quaint in the days of #metoo  #creativityplus #creativecatalyst #fashionmemories #fashionmeme #miniskirt #thatdress #scandal #scandalous #shocking #shock #upsetting #upset #jeanshrimpton #ladyhasstyle #memoriesmade #memoriesforlife #thegoodolddays #quaint #nearlynaked #revealing #timeheals #changingperspective #newfashion #modellifestyle #derbyday #celebratinglife  #thesixties #fashionfauxpas

text:
#metoo #toxicmasculinity #whyididntreport. iâ€™ll engage with the social media; i'll have the conversations. but that's it. after all ... this isn't really about me - right??
.
it's so half-ass. it's not enough. and it's not true, either. i've lived these dynamics in past relationships and in my relationship with my partner,Â @taliagutin.
.
no, i'm not talking about rape or sexual assault. yes, i am talking about the underlying power dynamics, trust and mistrust, shame, aggression and fear of vulnerability that create the space for rape and sexual assault to happen.
.
i've been the dominant, aggressive male who gets off on control; i've also been the mr. nice guy, who is eager to please and unwilling to stand up for himself. and my partner, talia, has been both the submissive woman who felt powerless in a past relationship and the independent "i don't need you" woman who closed off emotionally to her partner in another.
.
we see couples all around us who are in their own state of disharmony. they are not #metoo'ing. and they are also not thriving.
ghandi said: "if you want to change the world, start with yourself." the same holds true of relationships. let's transform the dynamics between men and women by growing our relationship with our partner first.
.
we know a lot of relationship coaches and therapists. we don't many coaching duo's who work incredibly well together and are also in a deeply committed, loving relationship with each other.
.
we're looking for three other couples who want to join ... who want to do their part in changing the way that men and women engage with one another in our country and recognize that it starts with their own relationship.
.
our program - 'thriving couples - is 10 sessions over 5 months. you'll work 1:1 with both talia and me, and we'll work in group sessions with your partner, talia and me. it's different from other coaching and therapy models we've seen for couples, and we're offering a significant discount for the next three couples to sign up.
.
link with more in my bio.
.
dm me if you or someone you know might be interested. let's create the change we need in this country, together - one vote and one couple at a time.
.

text:
your vote, your future. 
just a quick psa for #travelers like me, you can still vote from out of the country!

instructions: make sure you are registered to vote at your permanent address in the u.s. (use vote.org to confirm your registration), then email your county supervisor of elections and request an absentee ballot by email. they will email you a ballot which you have the option to either print and mail physically through a certified mail service, or print and fax to them directly. do all of this weeks or months in advance! your vote is worth it.

if you are unsure of who to vote for, there are awesome online resources to help educate you on who is running. yes, ballots can get confusing!  there are even sample ballots based on your party affiliation that can help to guide you. get on instagram, utilize google, talk to your friends, ask questions, join the conversation and rock your vote!

vote as if the future depends on you, because it does. your voice matters.

text:
kenyette barnes has been trying to silence @rkelly since her college days in the early 2000s. but only recently has the country started listening.
.
.
barnes, an #atlanta lobbyist and activist, is the co-founder of #muterkelly, a social media movement akin to #metoo or #timesup, designed to diminish the controversial singerâ€™s influence the music world. that includes concerts like the one scheduled for saturday at the #yuenglingcenter in #tampa.
.
.
professors and students at the #universityofsouthflorida last week launched a petition to have the concert canceled or moved from the yuengling center. (it was booked not by the university or the arenaâ€™s management company, but as a facility rental by an out-of-state promoter.) barnes, whose movement has followed #rkelly in concert for more than a year, swiftly got on board. theyâ€™ll keep pressure on university and venue officials up until the show, with a possible protest outside the arena on saturday.
.
.
"this has just happened for too long without any degree of accountability," barnes said. "this movement will mobilize these activists to say, â€˜hey, this is not just two or three people, this is a movement.â€™"

text: â€œi decided to start anew, to strip away what i had been taught.â€ georgia oâ€™keeffe photograph by her husband. i have always been a big follower and her life and art but up until i became a mother, did i really ever grasp itâ€™s true meaning.  i remember when i first became a mother, i felt that i was suddenly accepted into this secret world i never knew existed. when woman co-workers or just random woman on the street discovered i was a mother suddenly their looks changed .... like you know what life is about and the struggle we share. even so, i found this new role to be shocking and unwelcome as i was suddenly being forced be someone i was not ... it ate away at me until i decided that i donâ€™t have to be a personal maid, chef, nurse, and chauffeur to my family. itâ€™s okay to demand help or me time, or for my husband to sacrifice his career goals for mine. i have been trying to strip away these misconceptions in order to become a better, happier, balanced mother and role model for my daughter. what about you? what misconceptions as a new mother have you battled and how, if so, have you overcame them? #mothers #womanempowerment #womanquotes #metoo #motherhood #motherhoodunplugged #firsttimemother #womanhood #femalepower #georgiaokeeffe #inspirationalwoman #feminism #feminist

text:
rose news sexual harassment
two manuu students in hyd allege sexual misconduct by head of journalism department
the department head allegedly made sexual advancements towards both students, and even offered one student money in exchange for sex.

the #metoo movement against harassers in academia began last year after a curated list was released by student and lawyer raya sarkar. now, two students from maulana azad national urdu university in hyderabad have come forward with allegations of sexual misconduct against the head of journalism department, ehtesham ahmad.

tasleem begum, a student of the 2017 batch of the mass communication and journalism course, said she refused alleged sexual advances towards her by ehtesham last year. â€œit all started with the hod, ehtesham ahmad, asking me to meet him outside the university, privately. he even offered me money in exchange for sex if i meet him. i did not know how to react, did not raise any complaint and started avoiding him,â€ tasleem, who is from an economically poor background, alleged. 
tasleemâ€™s father works as a fruit vendor in the streets of hyderabad, she is the first woman in her family to attend a university. â€œever since he made such an advance, even if i wanted an out pass from the hostel i would meet him only in the presence of people. i would take effort never to be in the same room with him alone but then he started noticing that i was avoiding him,â€ she said.

text: a client of mine was assaulted as a child by someone close to her. fast forward a couple decades and she found herself alone, no children and a two time divorcee. she had a hard time being intimate with men and felt dirty after intercourse. after a few sessions i began to probe into her past and found out about her assault, an assault she never healed from, never spoke about. little did she know, this assault and the emotions that were tied to it were setting the mold for each and every relationship she had with the opposite sex. it took a while but she began to deal with those suppressed feelings and acknowledged those common traits between the men she chose to be intimate with and her abuser. sometimes our past unconsciously affects our future and creates these negative cycles that feel like they are impossible to break. taking time to acknowledge, go through, talk it out, and heal is the healthiest way to break the cycle and stop the repetition.

text:
v for vendetta (6/8) "remember, remember, the 5th of november..."
as the world is going towards a direction that seems to speak only words of hate, that seems to have as its one and only purpose to strip away human rights from as many people as possible, and as we approach here in new york an election day that feels as crucial as it ever has, i feel like sharing this old monologue i recorded from v for vendetta.
because only love can make us fearless. and if we don't learn to love each other, to protect each other, to support and have hope for each other, even for those we don't know, there will be no tomorrow, no hope, and no light to beak through these dark, dark days.
and, once again: for all the times i've been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you don't want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i've been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an artist, as a free person and an activist, this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i won't stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you don't agree with it, fine. but you won't shut my mouth, you won't stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.

text: when women say men are trash, most of the times it's not because some boyfriend broke their heart. it's the anger that comes from centuries of systematic oppression, it's because men are much, much more likely to assault (sexual or otherwise) women than vice versa. it's because almost every girl today has been catcalled at least once and it's because men are again, much more likely to be pedophiles than women even though the latter is possible. it's because of sexism that women face and while men do often face sexism, those of you who think they're the victims, specially in pakistan, aren't? why? because when we talk about sexism that men face, we are talking about toxic masculinity, men not being allowed to wear makeup, men not being able to play the roles that society assigned to women originally, men not being able to be feminine or wear feminine clothes. now that's sexism. oh, and men getting laughed at when they comeout with a #metoo story. and by the way, men who get triggered by men are trash are the same ones more often than not to engage in above mentioned sexism. you having to give up your seat in a metro bus in pakistan for a woman who probably doesn't know the first thing about feminism (due to lack of awareness) isn't sexism. i agree though, we should avoid using the three words you so very quickly get triggered by but then you make sexist as hell memes, you say sexist as hell stuff, you do misogynistic shit and then have the nerve to wonder why women say men are trash. and for the record, nobody thinks that all men are trash but as a guy if you consider yourself one of the good ones but make no effort to correct your sexist buddies then you're probably not. still, i get that generalising is not cool but why is it that you're all seen in the replies of men are trash tweets, and that too very angry, but when the time comes for tweets that are sexist you guys are no where to be seen? that shows where your priorities are and further proves that you don't consider women rights human rights.

text:
i took this picture last week but never got around to sharing it. today, i need to remind myself of the beauty in this world, especially today.
â€¢
yesterday was not a good day...full of self doubt & heavy emotions still lingering from my sunday night meeting. then a text comes through not meant for me but it was about me where the person referred to me as â€œpigâ€. now i have taken away this persons power to hurt me long ago, but yesterday was different as i was already hypersensitive emotionally...the tears just instantly flowed bc i have worked so hard to change not only my outward appearance, but my inner self too.  itâ€™s hurtful bc of who they are & who i am in relation to them...that iâ€™m still referred to as â€œpigâ€ in their eyes after all these years.
â€¢
today, a complete stranger, whom i have never met, spoke words to me that remind me of whose opinion matters the most.  he said â€œplease donâ€™t think this is weird, but i felt i have to tell you that jesus loves you & wants you to know you are doing the right thing.  he wanted me to tell you.â€ i was at a complete loss for words & just said thank you.
â€¢
thank you god for the reminder when i needed it most.
â€¢
#faithhopelove #teamburninitdown #devineintervention #jesuslovesme #imperfectinhiseyes

text:
the sign that i wore on my back at the first #womensmarch to reach out to other survivors, so they might finally be able to forgive themselves for what was done to them, and begin healing. â™¥ï¸ ***trigger warning for survivors of sexual violence and abuse*** my favorite part of the march was when a very young girl approached me to thank me, and very sheepishly asked if she could hug me! :') she could not have been more than fourteen years old (the age that i was when i was raped)... ğŸ’”

as we embraced, my eyes filled with tears as they met her mother's who was standing just a few feet away, and she mouthed the words "thank you!" ğŸ’œğŸ’œğŸ’œ it was never our fault. 
the shame belongs only to the perpetrators of abuse.

thank you for changing the world with us! ğŸ’ªğŸ¼ğŸ˜ŠğŸŒğŸ’– #bethechange 
#bethelight ğŸ”¥
#darknesscannotsurvivelight 
______________________________ "they 'let you' do it..." those words triggered my anxiety like a fireball to the chest... it felt like my stomach dropped down outside of my body, and the fog (fear, obligation, and guilt) was back.. when targeted by a dangerous and/or powerful predator that is too strong to defeat, our bodies are triggered to freeze... for survivors of domestic or sexual violence/abuse, or other traumatic violence, we know all too well what can happen when we are faced with the dilemma of trying not to escalate a situation where a violent person has decided that you are their target or prey. :ğŸ˜• please understand that survivors of abuse don't just "'let them' (sexual predators or abusers) do anything"... they are having a natural response to intense trauma that they feel they can not escape safely, and they are literally frozen in terror and shock. â˜¹ï¸ read and share this information to help us remove the stigma from survivors of sexual violence/assault/and abuse for "not fighting back". our brains and bodies literally preserved our safety and lives in a completely natural way. 
don't be so hard on yourself if you froze when you were attacked. many people do. please don't be cruel to yourself anymore. no matter how many people have blamed you, it was never your fault. 
continued in comments...

and our privilege,

we open the way, widen the way, change the way

text:
i voted because my life literally depends on it. i am thankful for the access to hormones, surgeries, ability to change my name and gender marker on legal documents, that discrimination against trans people is illegal (in most circumstances), voters who can see beyond themselves. 
i voted for trans rights, but also for women, children, gun control, corrupt politicians (hey chicago), a dishonest president, immigrants, tax appropriation, because black lives matter, and because it is my right to have my voice heard!

text:
i am falling short of words and short of breath. i am losing the patience but yes i am high on mental strength. i am going to achieve what i want to. i am running out of patience and this is not a self-pity rant. these are questions that i ask, as a girl who has to struggle for some unnecessary things. why? why does it matter if i am unmarried? why does it matter if i choose to stay all by myself? why? why the fuck, does it matter? why my work, my achievements, which may be nothing for you, doesn't matter. so if it doesn't then also its fine. but don't, don't walk over me, don't insult me ever, because i am going to run over you, by my work and my success, whenever it shall arrive.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

text:
dear bpd,

iâ€™ve been putting up with you for so long now and i needed to write to you to get my head around how i am feeling.
-
having you around all the time is exhausting and iâ€™m not even sure why. you make me tired all the time and my memory is shocking because of you.
i wake up to a battle in my head everyday fighting my emotions. i have to remind myself everyday that i am good enough because you make me feel like my friends and family hate me, like they donâ€™t want me and that puts so much strain on relationships. do you know how many friends i have lost?
-
one wrong word, one wrong look, anything that feels like rejection is rejection.
my heart breaks then i obsess about it because somehow i feel like i could have done better.
i pick things apart, read into every text, every phone call. it's a war zone in my own mind that never ever ends.
trying to control everything in my head is exhausting and i donâ€™t even know what it is iâ€™m trying to control.
i want to be alone but i don't because i canâ€™t stand to be lonely.
when i do make a connection, i attach myself. i obsess because that's what i do. i develop a â€œfavourite personâ€ and they are my everything.
no calls, no messages, is rejection. it doesn't matter the reason. i become overbearing, annoying. bad enough that i push people away. then i end up alone and then i blame myself for being alone when all i wanted was to be loved. 
some days it feels like i don't have a heart, then other days it feels like it's going to explode out of my chest because i love so much. 
some days suck, some days are great, perfect even but iâ€™ll never know what each day holds.
-
iâ€™m always exhausted but never able to sleep.
-
but bpd i promise i will mute you, i will silence you with medication and therapy. i will silence you by not listening to you and by believing i am worthy, by surrounding myself with love.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
healing from trauma:â €
â €
it has been sometime since the #metoo movement, which revealed an all too common secret of how many have endured some form of sexual abuse. â €
â €
the question is "what now?" how does one heal from sexual trauma?  as someone, who is an incest survivor, now learning how to thrive into a life i chose; i am learning how to work with what has been unwillingly given to me. i am learning how to integrate the truths of my past by relinquishing its control on the now through the various triggers that freeze aspect of myself still. â €
â €
in honor of myself and others who are silently walking these steps, i am going to dedicate a new series of blogs, videos, and open up options in how to heal through trauma.  first, how to identify it and recognize it. second, how to ground within it. third, how to reclaim power back by bringing back soul fragramants that have the trauma frozen with our body's and the corners of the mind.  fourth, share different forms of therapies that maybe a good fit to build within your self care toolbox. â €
â €

text:
v for vendetta (7/8) "remember, remember, the 5th of november..."
as the world is going towards a direction that seems to speak only words of hate, that seems to have as its one and only purpose to strip away human rights from as many people as possible, and as we approach here in new york an election day that feels as crucial as it ever has, i feel like sharing this old monologue i recorded from v for vendetta.
because only love can make us fearless. and if we don't learn to love each other, to protect each other, to support and have hope for each other, even for those we don't know, there will be no tomorrow, no hope, and no light to beak through these dark, dark days.
and, once again: for all the times i've been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you don't want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i've been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an artist, as a free person and an activist, this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i won't stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you don't agree with it, fine. but you won't shut my mouth, you won't stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.
#5thofnovember #vforvendetta #agirlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
join us tomorrow november 7 from 6 â€“ 7pm for an artist talk with ingrid vb porter titled â€œthe intersection of art, mythology and personal process.â€ free and open to the public.  her exhibition other worldly is on display at art gym november 1-23, 2018.
.
other worldly, by ingrid vb porter, performs an investigation into how an artistâ€™s personal mythology and metaphor plays into their individual practice. with a background in archetypal art therapy, porter uses her practice to create art that helps the viewer explore their own lives. speaking on this, porter states â€œi find the intersection of personal story, mythology and psychology to be a rich, fascinating and rewarding placeâ€¦these elements bring new â€“ and often unexpected â€“ layers of meaning to my paintings and illustrated stories.â€ one example of this is porterâ€™s new book titled #me too â€“ persephone which recontextualizes the classic greek myth in the current #metoo movement.

text:
i was sexually abused by my brother from 4-10 years old.. he was 12-17. on top of that pain my father molested me at the age of 12 in my sleep. i can tell you my hearts never been so broken from this. due to the abuse i suffer from diagnosed ptsd but am determined to chase my goals despite my circumstances. while no one saved me i saved myself and took a stance in february & reported the abuse to the police. although this has been the most difficult process iâ€™ve ever been through, iâ€™m putting a stop to these men ever hurting another like they did me. iâ€™m standing up for the men and women who couldnâ€™t stand up or decided not to. iâ€™m standing up for my future children. iâ€™ve become stronger and more empowered from this. although the process has been hard and long, justice is being served. sentencing for both my brother david and my father are happening by the end of this year due to them pleading guilty to the charges. 
i donâ€™t normally share this but itâ€™s nothing to be ashamed about and abuse is no one but the abusers fault. the topic should be talked about more often. no one saved me but iâ€™m proud i saved myself. if you feel like you need someone & have been through a similar situation please message me as i wonâ€™t judge. itâ€™s time to put a stop to what these men and women do. #metoo #staystrong #saveyourself

text:
so your ex broke up with you, and now you find yourself snooping through their social media pics, only to be hurt even more by seeing your ex having the time of his/her life. . .keep these things in mind:
â–«what you see on social media is not always as it seems.
â–«by snooping, you're slowing down your healing process, like ripping the band-aid off a wound.
. â–«there's a chance your ex is posting those pics *hoping* you will see them so you can feel horrible (especially if they've already moved on to someone else).
.
do yourself several favors: remind yourself that if the ex really cared, then they wouldn't be trying so hard to make you feel bad. take the time you need to heal from the breakup, and quit inviting more pain into your life by stalking his/her social media pages. you can do this! ğŸ’ª ğŸ’¯
.
